ess-date=2019-12-14}}</ref> In 2016 ''Food52'' called it a hack that works.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://food52.com/blog/18016-we-tested-21-viral-internet-food-hacks-some-really-do-work|title=We Tested 21 Viral Internet Food Hacks\u2014& Some Really Do Work!|last=Jampel|first=Sarah|date=2016-09-27|website=Food52|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref> ''Scientific American'' used the method in 2017 as one of their Bring Science Home series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/separation-science-suck-up-an-egg-yolk/|title=Separation Science: Suck up an Egg Yolk|last=Arnett|first=Megan|date=21 December 2017|website=Scientific American|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref>  \n\nIn March 2019 a hack showing how to eat a pineapple without first peeling or coring it was popular.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://food52.com/blog/23918-pineapple-hack-viral-internet-trick|title=The Pineapple Hack That\u2019s Taking Over the Internet Right Now|last=Lo|first=Karen|date=2019-03-12|website=Food52|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref> In October a video showing how to seed a pomegranate was popular.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5706083/how-to-slice-a-pomegranate-hack/|title=The Latest Food Hack to Grace Your Eyeballs Is This Mesmerizing Pomegranate Slicing Method|last=Greenspan|first=Rachel|date=21 October 2019|website=Time|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref>\n\nThere are multiple methods for peeling garlic.<ref name=\":1\" /> One method involves shaking garlic between two metal bowls or in a [[mason jar]].<ref name=\":1\" /> ''[[Good Housekeeping]]'' called the method \"not a win.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodhousekeeping.com/food-recipes/cooking/a29741594/viral-food-hacks/|title=We Tested Viral Food Hacks to See If They R