were dangerous, such as cooking foil-wrapped bacon in an upright toaster, which toaster manufacturers said could cause fires or electrical shock.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/long-story-short-my-microwave-exploded-the-problem-with-life-hack-videos-11570636955|title=Why Life Hack Videos Seem Too Good to Be True. (They Are)|last=Horwitz|first=Jeff|date=2019-10-09|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2019-12-14|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> In 2019 [[Today (American TV program)|''Today'']] investigated multiple popular cooking hacks and declared some of them dangerous.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.today.com/food/5-viral-kitchen-hacks-are-actually-dangerous-t160893|title=5 viral kitchen hacks that are actually dangerous|last=|first=|date=19 August 2019|website=TODAY.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Culinary terminology]]\n[[Category:Food and drink terminology]]\n[[Category:Hacker culture]]\n[[Category:Life skills]]\n", "name_user": "Coffeeandcrumbs", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kitchen_hack"}
